Not a problem, and don’t worry—most of the book is in good shape w/r/t correct pagination; it’s just the chapter/part openers through chapter 6. Essentially, any new section that would be listed in the table of contents should appear on a right-hand (odd-numbered) page. This includes the acknowledgments and preface (as well as things like forewords, lists of tables or figures, abbreviations, introductions, and other things like that). If a section ends on a right-hand page, you add a blank page afterward to force the next section onto a right-hand page as well. I know Yasuyo marked them in the last round, but I added blank pages to the PDF so you can use it as a basis of comparison when you’re moving things around for the next set of proofs. If you haven’t already, it helps if you use two page view in Acrobat (View > Page Display > Two Page View or Two Page Scrolling) and check off the option to view the first page as if it were a front cover (View > Page Display > Show Cover Page in Two Page View).

 

As for the frontmatter, this is how the pages should be ordered (and I’ve written this out in a sticky note in the PDF as well, just in case):

 

i – half title

ii – blank page

iii – title page

iv – copyright page

v – dedication

vi – blank page

vii – first page of TOC

and any subsequent sections should begin on an odd-numbered, right-hand page (so, in this case, acknowledgments on xxiii, preface on xxv, with blank pages added as needed). I’ve inserted the blank pages and moved the dedication to page v so you can see what the finished PDF should look like.

 

